Content:
Well,  I wrote a simple blog engine after finishing the chapter
although I don't use a database here,  the blog is saved directly to
disk (<a href="http://github.com/l0stman/Blog" rel="nofollow">http://github.com/l0stman/Blog</a>).<p>The biggest hurdle with Common Lisp is configuring the system
correctly because there's no out of the box solution.  Although
there's a lot of library -- <a href="http://www.cliki.net" rel="nofollow">http://www.cliki.net</a> is a great resource
-- figuring out how to use asdf-install is a bit painful.  I took me
almost four days to figure out how to launch Hunchentoot as a daemon
at startup under FreeBSD
(<a href="http://github.com/l0stman/Hunchentoot-daemon" rel="nofollow">http://github.com/l0stman/Hunchentoot-daemon</a>).  In my case, the lisp
server itself lays behind nginx as a proxy.  The latter serves the
static pages too.  Here's nginx's configuration:<p><pre><code>     server {
        listen       80;
        server_name  localhost;

        location / {
            root   /usr/local/www/nginx;
            # Use absract URL for static pages
            try_files $uri.html $uri/index.html $uri $uri.txt @fallback;
        }

        location @fallback {
            return 404;
        }

        # redirect server error pages to the static page /50x.html
        #
        error_page   500 502 503 504  /50x.html;
        location = /50x.html {
            root   /usr/local/www/nginx-dist;
        }

        # Tunnel all requests where the URI path begins with "/ht"
        # to a Hunchentoot server listening on 127.0.0.1:8080
        #
        location /ht/ {
            rewrite ^/ht/(.*)$ /$1 break;
            proxy_pass   http://127.0.0.1:8080;
            proxy_redirect http://127.0.0.1:8080 /ht;
            proxy_read_timeout 300;
        }
    }</code></pre>
